It&#x27;s a bit radical, but I am tempted to test it. :)<p>I am wiseleo on just about every website and gmail, so feel free to send me an instant message.<p>For me, seeing an executable test spec for the first time was very surprising and revealing. There is an entire book &quot;Refactoring: improving the design of existing code&quot; that teaches you how to name functions so your code reads like English.<p>After all, this is valid Jasmine from near the beginning of my test suite:<p>it(&quot;should return an array containing at least one object&quot;, function() {
  expect(menu.length).toBeGreaterThan(0);
});<p>It reads like English. If you can show that code can be written like this rather than like typical code, you will notice an immediate jump in confidence.<p>If you show that in Rspec, where the alien-looking<p>function (
  ) {
};<p>is replaced with<p><pre><code>  do</code></pre>
end<p>and expect(&#x27;should do something useful&#x27;) becomes expect &quot;should do something useful&quot;<p>it becomes even more approachable.
